# Supported microcontrollers and why

Any device that can do **HTTP POST** (or WebSocket) over the network and send **binary frame data** (e.g. JPEG) can use this project.

## Requirements

- **Network:** WiFi or Ethernet (or other IP connectivity to the server).
- **HTTP client:** Ability to POST to `http(s)://YOUR_SERVER/api/device/stream/:streamId/frame` with headers and a binary body, **or** a WebSocket client to connect and send auth + binary frames.
- **Frames:** Capture or generate image data (typically JPEG) and send it as the request body or as WebSocket binary messages.

## Recommended / commonly used

| Platform | Why it works |
|----------|----------------|
| **ESP32-CAM** | Built-in camera, WiFi, Arduino ecosystem. Use `HTTPClient` or `WiFiClient` to POST each JPEG from `camera_fb_t->buf`. Very common for low-cost camera streaming. |
| **Raspberry Pi** | Full Linux, WiFi/Ethernet, Python or any language. Use `requests.post(url, data=jpeg_bytes, headers={...})` or `urllib.request`. Can use USB or CSI cameras and encode to JPEG. |
| **Arduino + Ethernet/WiFi shield** | Can build HTTP requests manually or use a small HTTP library. Good for wired Ethernet or WiFi boards (e.g. Arduino Uno + Ethernet Shield, or ESP8266/ESP32). |
| **ESP8266 / ESP32** | WiFi, HTTP client libraries, enough RAM to hold and send small JPEGs (ESP32-CAM is the camera variant). |
| **Other Linux SBCs** (e.g. Orange Pi, BeagleBone) | Same idea as Raspberry Pi: run a small script that captures frames and POSTs them. |

## Why HTTP (device API) exists

Many microcontrollers have limited or no WebSocket support, but can do HTTP easily. The device extension adds a simple REST API so those devices only need to POST one frame per request with a password header. The server then feeds those frames into the same in-memory stream and WebSocket viewer pipeline, so behavior is identical to a browser broadcaster.

## When editing device code

- Keep **streamId** lowercase, 1–64 chars.
- Send **Content-Type: image/jpeg** (or appropriate type) for frame POSTs.
- Auth: **X-Stream-Password** or **Authorization: Bearer &lt;password&gt;**.
- Max body size per frame request: **~5 MB** (server limit in `device-extension.js`).
- Reference: `docs/DEVICE-API.md` for curl examples and WebSocket option.
